WEBVTT

00:02.338 --> 00:02.759
Good morning.

00:03.140 --> 00:03.460
How are you?

00:05.364 --> 00:08.330
I am going to be doing something that's really fun this morning.

00:09.252 --> 00:10.434
Back by popular demands.

00:10.454 --> 00:15.444
Remember when I interviewed Mike, Liz and Bola, and we had a brilliant time up here.

00:16.767 --> 00:17.508
Some time ago now.

00:17.688 --> 00:19.271
I'm going to be doing an interview in just a moment.

00:20.754 --> 00:22.578
To glean some wisdom.

00:22.690 --> 00:24.793
from multiple sources about today's topic.

00:25.213 --> 00:28.737
Because we have been looking at the theme of the Lord's Prayer.

00:29.138 --> 00:31.941
It has been and is incredible, isn't it?

00:32.001 --> 00:34.605
Are you loving going deep and lingering in each line?

00:34.705 --> 00:35.305
I know I am.

00:36.667 --> 00:47.500
It's been fantastic hearing about God being our Father, about his name being hallowed and what that means, about his kingdom coming and his will being done on earth as it is in heaven.

00:47.560 --> 00:48.882
Dave last week,

00:48.994 --> 00:50.135
would give us our daily bread.

00:50.155 --> 00:51.697
We had a guest speaker, Dave Boden.

00:51.817 --> 00:57.082
If you haven't had a chance to listen, do, if you were here and you've had a listen or you listened at home, listen again.

00:57.142 --> 01:06.030
Because I just was watching people writing as he was just speaking amazing nugget, brilliant truth, loads and loads of times and people couldn't really keep up.

01:06.491 --> 01:09.353
So I didn't bother writing, but I do definitely need to listen again.

01:09.814 --> 01:16.080
It was amazing and how we can be dependent on the new thing that God has for each day and not the stale things of yesterday.

01:16.540 --> 01:18.322
And his talk of bread

01:18.754 --> 01:22.778
was fantastic and got us all thinking about lovely French bread.

01:23.298 --> 01:28.964
I know it was for me, and we've got communion later, but that will be little cubes of gluten-free, not quite the same.

01:29.244 --> 01:31.026
But he still gives us our daily bread.

01:31.046 --> 01:36.651
Now, right in the middle of the Lord's Prayer comes the line we know.

01:36.711 --> 01:39.915
Forgive us our sins as we forgive those who sin against us.

01:40.775 --> 01:43.298
Or forgive us our trespasses or whatever it is our wrongdoings.

01:44.059 --> 01:47.602
And I thought it would be really good for us to just spend some time

01:47.778 --> 01:54.005
listening to other people who've had loads of experience of journeying with people through the process of forgiveness.

01:54.746 --> 01:56.207
It's a central theme in the Bible.

01:57.669 --> 02:01.834
All the way through we see that forgiveness is the key and Israel in the Old Testament.

02:02.374 --> 02:03.475
They're journeying with God.

02:03.876 --> 02:05.558
They make some bad decisions.

02:05.618 --> 02:06.879
They fall away from God.

02:06.939 --> 02:07.540
They repent.

02:07.620 --> 02:08.321
They're forgiven.

02:08.721 --> 02:11.684
They're back into a time of blessing and then they fall away again.

02:11.745 --> 02:14.267
They make some bad decisions and then they repent.

02:14.307 --> 02:16.690
They're forgiven and the journey goes on and on.

02:17.090 --> 02:24.487
We see Joseph giving us a brilliant demonstration of what forgiveness looks like when his brothers return into Egypt and he's able to forgive them.

02:25.429 --> 02:36.114
We see stories of Moses being frustrated, leading the people beautifully but going to get water the second time out of a rock and he

02:36.226 --> 02:38.710
doesn't do it in the way that God tells him to do it.

02:38.810 --> 02:41.715
And God said, because of that, you can't enter the promised land.

02:42.176 --> 02:43.117
You see, what's that about?

02:43.177 --> 02:45.641
Why can't he be forgiven for that little thing?

02:45.701 --> 02:47.524
Why is he able to go into the promised land?

02:47.885 --> 02:49.087
We know he is forgiven.

02:49.167 --> 02:51.450
Ultimately, the transfiguration, he's there.

02:51.510 --> 02:56.378
We know that he's forgiven eternally, but why would that take place?

02:56.458 --> 02:56.979
Why was it?

02:57.039 --> 02:59.784
He couldn't go into the promised land if God is so forgiving.

03:00.184 --> 03:01.266
What's all that about?

03:01.570 --> 03:02.832
There are so many questions.

03:03.252 --> 03:14.910
In the Mosaic law, blood sacrifices were established for the forgiveness of sins, and ultimately Jesus would pay the ultimate blood sacrifice price for the forgiveness of sins.

03:15.811 --> 03:16.832
We are forgiven.

03:17.794 --> 03:27.007
We are able to live in relationship with God, our Father, because of the forgiveness that we get through the death and resurrection of Jesus.

03:27.749 --> 03:29.151
That is why we are here today.

03:29.211 --> 03:31.474
It has made all the difference.

03:31.906 --> 03:37.573
And in the middle of this prayer, it says, forgive us our sins as we forgive those who sin against us.

03:37.653 --> 03:41.798
And I've done a couple of messages on forgiveness before, so you could go back and have a look.

03:42.939 --> 03:50.048
But it's interesting that in this particular part of the Lord's prayer, it says, forgive us our sins as we forgive those.

03:50.469 --> 03:52.611
It's the one that's got the claws attached to it.

03:53.432 --> 03:58.679
And actually, at the bottom of the Lord's prayer, it says, if you don't forgive those who sin against you, your father won't forgive you.

03:58.699 --> 04:01.522
It's quite direct.

04:02.018 --> 04:05.962
more direct than sometimes we like to imagine or appreciate.

04:06.883 --> 04:08.144
So why is there this clause?

04:08.604 --> 04:13.209
In the way that we've received forgiveness from God, we need to extend that forgiveness to others.

04:14.470 --> 04:15.151
That's hard to do.

04:15.191 --> 04:17.333
It's hard to do.

04:18.454 --> 04:19.876
We are not God and He is.

04:20.596 --> 04:27.363
And the journey of forgiveness and working out how to do it and what it looks like, that they're important questions for us as the church to wrestle with.

04:28.904 --> 04:30.546
And so we're going to do that a little bit this morning.

04:31.234 --> 04:48.444
And I would love to invite up to the platform, Bola Liz and Freddie slash Mike.

04:55.176 --> 04:56.338
It's like question time.

05:01.186 --> 05:01.627
Amazing.

05:01.707 --> 05:02.227
Thank you guys.

05:02.307 --> 05:03.108
I'll go here at the end.

05:10.217 --> 05:11.078
You say question time or this is your life.

05:11.098 --> 05:11.539
Give it that.

05:14.322 --> 05:15.524
Don't worry, there's no red book.

05:16.845 --> 05:18.407
Freddie, I'd love to do this is your life for you.

05:18.627 --> 05:19.949
It'd be so good.

05:19.969 --> 05:30.482
For those of you who have no idea what that means, that's anyone from my age or a year below me, if you're 51 or younger, that didn't mean anything that reference, but it was a good one for the oldies.

05:30.786 --> 05:35.013
Let me introduce you to the amazing people who are sitting next to me up here on the platform.

05:35.033 --> 05:35.594
This is Liz.

05:36.696 --> 05:40.041
Liz has been part of the church family for decades.

05:40.562 --> 05:42.325
She is a pillar in the life of the church.

05:42.385 --> 05:46.712
She was one of our congregational pastors along with her husband Paul for many, many years.

05:47.072 --> 05:55.506
She has headed up counseling in the church for many, many years and continues to do the same, even in your retirement from being employed.

05:55.682 --> 05:58.205
You are still an absolute legend and we lean on you.

05:58.285 --> 06:01.690
And so many of us have had our lives transformed because of what you do.

06:02.311 --> 06:02.751
So thank you.

06:04.494 --> 06:08.419
Mike Collins, real name Mike, I call him Freddie.

06:08.639 --> 06:12.745
I will interchange between those two names accidentally on purpose.

06:12.765 --> 06:19.173
But Mike's been being part of the worship team in this church, was part of the worship team for absolutely ages.

06:19.214 --> 06:22.578
He was telling me the other day that when he joined the church,

06:22.754 --> 06:31.122
the only person who's currently still part of the worship team, Linda Cloe, was the organist, and that was in 1975, Linda.

06:31.883 --> 06:32.784
No, don't tell anyone.

06:32.824 --> 06:33.505
Don't tell anyone that.

06:33.525 --> 06:35.587
It's 50 years in one worship department.

06:35.607 --> 06:37.088
That's pretty blooming good going.

06:38.189 --> 06:50.962
But then Freddy came in, brought a rock guitar in, Peter Sawyer, you know, sort of rocks off his chair by Fred is playing, and they've been part of this team for absolutely ages, where Nicky and I joined the church in 2001.

06:51.330 --> 06:54.575
Mike was there with Steve Crouch working hard into the worship.

06:54.595 --> 06:58.641
And I remember it being handed over to us in 2003 so graciously.

06:58.921 --> 07:08.295
And if you ever want to see how to pass the relay baton on well and cheer on the person who follows you brilliantly, Mike is an amazing example of that.

07:08.716 --> 07:15.225
A trained counselor and you have just given your life into this church and into the lives of so many for so long.

07:15.265 --> 07:18.450
So we just want to say thank you for that.

07:21.186 --> 07:31.018
Now, Bala is one of, you obviously just saw him playing bass, but he is also one of the congregational pastors here in the church along with his wife Tina.

07:31.339 --> 07:34.303
He's had pastoral roles in previous churches too.

07:34.743 --> 07:40.691
He is a man who has a heart to serve and follow and love Jesus well and to love people the same.

07:41.031 --> 07:47.179
If you have ever had any conversations with him, you will know that about him, but do get to know all three of these amazing people.

07:47.219 --> 07:49.682
Let's give him one more hand and I'll give him a question.

07:52.194 --> 07:58.840
OK, I'm going to start with a big question, a massive one about God's love and his forgiveness in your life.

07:58.900 --> 07:59.521
I'll start with you, Liz.

07:59.861 --> 08:02.384
How has the forgiveness of God changed your life?

08:04.406 --> 08:05.387
Yeah, huge question.

08:05.827 --> 08:12.353
I think if I didn't know that God had forgiven me, I would not have a relationship with him.

08:13.174 --> 08:21.522
And if I didn't have a relationship with him, my life would be anything but what it is now.

08:21.634 --> 08:31.090
It's the transformation, isn't it, from being in a relationship with our Lord and Heavenly Father and not being in a relationship?

08:31.611 --> 08:35.998
You can't be in a relationship with anybody where there's unforgiveness.

08:36.819 --> 08:43.250
And so if I didn't know that I was forgiven, I would not be able to call myself a child of the God.

08:44.322 --> 08:44.723
That's great.

08:44.763 --> 08:45.324
Thank you, Liz.

08:45.344 --> 08:46.946
And that's a big sentence, isn't it?

08:46.966 --> 08:49.069
That you can't be in relationship with this unforgiveness.

08:49.129 --> 08:51.994
And we're going to be journeying through this and what this looks like.

08:52.374 --> 08:53.376
That's a big statement.

08:53.396 --> 08:53.817
Thank you.

08:54.037 --> 08:54.958
Freddie, same question to you.

08:54.978 --> 08:57.763
How has the love and forgiveness of God transformed your life?

09:00.587 --> 09:09.000
When I first become a Christian, recognizing that, it gave my life focus at a certain purpose, I think, being forgiven.

09:09.080 --> 09:12.786
I didn't fully understand that I needed to be forgiven.

09:13.154 --> 09:15.857
because I've done nothing wrong, as it were.

09:15.877 --> 09:28.530
I still remember being at Billy Graham meeting there, and in the mission, which was 66, and he was there with a 2,000-piece choir, and we're all sinners.

09:28.550 --> 09:30.933
I switched off at that.

09:31.574 --> 09:39.442
I've been invited, one of our college friends there, he found Jesus big time, and it was at the refractory there, having breakfast, and he said,

09:39.522 --> 09:40.123
Would you come on?

09:40.163 --> 09:41.144
Yes, I'll come on.

09:41.164 --> 09:43.125
I'm open to all these new ideas.

09:43.866 --> 09:46.729
And for being on, I switched off.

09:47.369 --> 09:56.658
The irony was, come the early 80s, I'm outgoing very mistake knocking on doors, taking people to the Billy Graham Mission to England in 1984.

09:57.239 --> 09:58.520
God has a sense of humor.

09:58.820 --> 10:00.502
But it gave my life focus.

10:01.042 --> 10:09.010
But I didn't fully understand coming to God what forgiveness actually was that I had sinned and I needed to

10:09.186 --> 10:11.490
if you establish that relationship with God.

10:12.412 --> 10:21.187
And that's what happens when you accept when you go to God and say, sorry, basically, and I'm forgiven.

10:21.267 --> 10:22.630
So great joy.

10:22.670 --> 10:23.712
Yeah, it's amazing.

10:23.732 --> 10:24.413
Thanks for that story.

10:24.433 --> 10:25.174
It's a good story.

10:25.234 --> 10:29.522
And yes, when Dave was here last week and speaking, he said, if you rewrote

10:29.666 --> 10:34.173
the Lord's Prayer in modern parlance, you may well sort of lose the forgiveness bit.

10:34.213 --> 10:35.435
I don't need any forgiveness.

10:35.715 --> 10:36.657
I don't do anything wrong.

10:36.817 --> 10:40.222
And so it's interesting that that's where your journey began too.

10:40.403 --> 10:40.863
You're a sinner.

10:40.944 --> 10:42.466
No, I haven't done anything.

10:42.486 --> 10:46.272
But it's getting the understanding and the revelation that has been transformational.

10:46.713 --> 10:48.836
Bola, how about you?

10:49.797 --> 10:52.642
I like Freddie, Mike.

10:53.463 --> 10:57.970
I knew I was a really, really bad sinner.

10:58.338 --> 11:02.166
I don't know some bad things, so I need that God in my life.

11:02.967 --> 11:04.149
So, yeah.

11:05.753 --> 11:10.883
So Jesus coming to my life and forgiving me, I knew that I needed God's forgiveness.

11:11.003 --> 11:12.646
And yeah, that was where I started.

11:12.686 --> 11:15.231
Yeah, so yeah.

11:15.251 --> 11:15.953
Brilliant, thank you.

11:16.313 --> 11:18.738
Now, when we moved into Chelmsford,

11:18.978 --> 11:19.900
in 2001.

11:20.781 --> 11:30.058
God was amazing and he orchestrated it that we would be in a semi-detached house attached to the current worship pastor and administrator here at the church.

11:31.140 --> 11:38.834
We didn't know of this church anything about it but God knew and he had plans for us and they taught us a great deal about forgiveness.

11:39.202 --> 11:40.384
and what forgiveness looked like.

11:40.825 --> 11:43.028
But I personally, a bit like Freddy, he was a fronted.

11:43.148 --> 11:47.936
I was a bit fronted sometimes because I felt it was a bit over the top the way they went about it.

11:48.356 --> 11:57.731
You see, they taught us that if your kids would need to say to you, I'm sorry, first part, and you would say to them, I forgive you.

11:58.852 --> 12:00.495
But that would happen in really small things.

12:01.196 --> 12:04.701
Like you'd say sorry for something to Steve and he'd say, I forgive you.

12:04.982 --> 12:07.666
And part of me is like, you don't need to say I forgive you.

12:08.034 --> 12:09.095
Just say, it's all right.

12:09.756 --> 12:10.257
It's okay.

12:10.737 --> 12:14.062
But I think that what we do very naturally is we say, oh, it's okay.

12:14.302 --> 12:15.504
When actually it isn't okay.

12:16.545 --> 12:18.507
What's happened may not be okay.

12:18.848 --> 12:22.913
Some of the things you may have forgiven people for in your life or you may need to forgive them for.

12:23.534 --> 12:24.455
They're not okay.

12:24.856 --> 12:34.428
And so for us to learn to say, I forgive you is actually a really powerful thing to do because it says it's not okay, but I still forgive you.

12:34.928 --> 12:36.210
And I remember,

12:36.386 --> 12:39.620
I used to watch this version of Cinderella.

12:40.082 --> 12:41.267
It's a very butch thing to do.

12:41.287 --> 12:43.858
It's called the slipper and the rose.

12:44.066 --> 12:50.033
a marvellous musical version, you'll be hard pressed to find it if it's ever downloadable, watch it.

12:50.053 --> 13:00.346
But anyway, in the end, Cinderella is so overjoyed that her life has been turned around, that she goes up to her stepmom and she says, and in my happiness, I forgive you all.

13:00.786 --> 13:05.051
And this stepmom says, forgive me, how dare she forgive me.

13:05.192 --> 13:07.194
And sometimes we can be like that too.

13:07.234 --> 13:10.578
If we say to somebody, I forgive you, they can be like,

13:11.010 --> 13:12.472
You don't just say, you forgive me.

13:12.512 --> 13:13.793
Don't take it too far.

13:14.054 --> 13:15.115
Who are you to forgive me?

13:15.195 --> 13:20.381
There's so much stuff that goes on and we can get so messed up in the middle of forgiveness.

13:20.401 --> 13:21.823
So here is a lovely question.

13:23.145 --> 13:23.465
Here we go.

13:23.485 --> 13:27.971
In the Lord's Prayer, we're clearly commanded to forgive others and that can be difficult.

13:28.671 --> 13:32.236
What does forgiveness look like in practice beyond saying, I forgive you?

13:32.416 --> 13:34.559
How do we actually forgive?

13:34.719 --> 13:35.940
What's this process look like?

13:36.761 --> 13:36.942
Okay.

13:37.562 --> 13:40.626
So I know

13:41.186 --> 13:44.950
When you forgive somebody, it's not saying what they did was okay.

13:45.611 --> 13:49.956
And it's not even saying, we are now okay, you and I are now okay.

13:50.097 --> 13:52.079
It's not like that with God, but with each other.

13:52.760 --> 13:58.627
It's like, what I'm doing when I forgive you is I am no longer seeing you through that lens.

13:58.707 --> 14:00.589
I'm no longer seeing you through that filter.

14:01.290 --> 14:06.676
So I'm choosing to see you outside of whatever it is that you did to me.

14:07.357 --> 14:08.018
Doesn't mean

14:08.418 --> 14:09.459
I like you.

14:10.200 --> 14:12.043
I want to be in relationship with you.

14:12.564 --> 14:16.229
But I am no longer going to judge you through what you did to me.

14:16.869 --> 14:18.251
So that's what it looks like.

14:18.652 --> 14:31.950
How we do it is an internal thing of choosing to not see them as the person who did X.

14:33.512 --> 14:38.098
But it's also working through the levels at which they've

14:38.370 --> 15:07.858
hurt you so if somebody's done something that's caused you to feel rejected it's not just that you've been rejected it's that that speaks to you about I'm I don't have worth I don't have value I I am less and and you have to forgive them for those things that have been laid on you because of their action so it's it's unpacking which is what a lot the counseling is about it's unpacking all of the

15:08.226 --> 15:13.512
ramifications of whatever it was that happened, and forgiving each of those things.

15:13.952 --> 15:21.701
And one of the things in the counseling that I used to encourage people to do was to write, not to send, but to write a letter.

15:22.722 --> 15:35.196
And in it to say, when you did X, it made me feel like this, but I choose to forgive you, so that you are actually looking at all of the consequences of whatever that action was.

15:36.097 --> 15:36.978
That's amazing.

15:37.314 --> 15:38.575
That's really useful, isn't it?

15:39.436 --> 15:44.262
I think already, I need to be getting all these questions over this clip out to life groups.

15:44.562 --> 15:48.887
People need to discuss this further, have a chat through it, because that was really good, a great answer.

15:48.927 --> 15:49.327
Thank you.

15:49.928 --> 15:54.793
It actually impacts us more than the event itself.

15:54.813 --> 15:56.976
It's all the things it triggers in us and unlocks in us.

15:57.056 --> 16:00.840
And I think the big thing about forgiveness is that we gain from it.

16:00.900 --> 16:04.184
It doesn't really matter to you whether I forgive you or not.

16:04.204 --> 16:06.066
You're not unless you're holding something.

16:06.210 --> 16:10.494
It's what it releases for me that is the thing.

16:11.215 --> 16:11.775
That's great.

16:12.256 --> 16:12.656
Thank you.

16:13.237 --> 16:14.578
Mike, same question to you.

16:14.678 --> 16:16.300
How do we do this forgiveness thing?

16:18.582 --> 16:35.698
I remember years ago, when I was working at a big chemical pharmaceutical company, saying to a champion in other departments, I'm sorry, I said that.

16:36.418 --> 16:39.602
And it was amazing, actually, transformation in the relationship.

16:40.903 --> 16:50.235
In those big companies, they have multidisciplinary meetings used to have departments, a lot of rivalry between departments.

16:51.256 --> 16:55.001
I was in the project, and he was in the building department.

16:55.121 --> 16:59.366
I even forget what it was, but it made amazing difference to our relationship.

17:00.227 --> 17:06.034
And because I forget what I said, but so that's sort of one instance.

17:06.242 --> 17:12.251
But the other thing that occurs to me is that forgiveness is not just a one-time thing.

17:13.353 --> 17:17.479
What about those people in relationship that you see daily?

17:18.120 --> 17:20.744
Maybe at home, maybe at work.

17:21.445 --> 17:22.026
What do you do?

17:22.426 --> 17:25.010
So even if you say, well, I'm sorry, I did that.

17:25.351 --> 17:26.152
Will you forgive me?

17:26.212 --> 17:32.622
On the one hand, on the other hand, in your mind.

17:32.642 --> 17:35.346
I mean, what if the person doesn't know they've upset you?

17:35.650 --> 17:38.534
You know, I'm waiting for you to say sorry, no.

17:38.554 --> 17:42.479
So, but, as we were saying, it's internal.

17:42.619 --> 17:44.422
What if somebody doesn't say sorry?

17:44.943 --> 17:45.864
Should we still forgive them?

17:46.665 --> 17:54.295
Yes, because in our own mind, there's some resentment there, some hurt, that is there, some offence.

17:54.776 --> 18:05.330
I still remember your thing about forgiveness and offence, lagging up a big piece of garden fence with you, because it actually disables you, you're lagging this thing about with you.

18:05.410 --> 18:07.852
So for your own benefit, you need to clear that.

18:07.872 --> 18:16.041
I think one of the roots to this is not forgetting that Jews come on is to love your neighbor as yourself.

18:16.981 --> 18:18.203
So that overrides this.

18:18.263 --> 18:27.171
And so is that next day, same person, this forgiving process is a continuous in this situation, I think.

18:27.892 --> 18:33.778
You've decided you set the direction to forgive that person, but you may have to carry on forgiving

18:34.306 --> 18:36.889
Each day are fresh, as you see them.

18:37.329 --> 18:37.930
Very useful.

18:38.050 --> 18:38.490
Thank you.

18:41.894 --> 18:43.976
Yeah, forgiveness.

18:45.537 --> 18:50.322
So the question was, how do we forgive?

18:50.342 --> 18:54.807
Well, how do we forgive?

18:55.067 --> 18:59.191
Forgiveness can be really, really difficult to actually give.

19:00.432 --> 19:02.034
And I'll be

19:02.210 --> 19:03.952
a little bit vulnerable here.

19:06.215 --> 19:08.438
Some years ago, I lost my dad, right?

19:08.619 --> 19:13.625
And what happened, my family situation is actually quite complicated.

19:13.665 --> 19:22.117
And in the process of having my dad buried under funeral, lots of things were said about me, really bad things.

19:22.858 --> 19:28.786
I got betrayed by really close people to me.

19:29.106 --> 19:31.890
And it was really, really painful.

19:32.642 --> 19:43.155
However, and every time I thought about those people, you know, I would have those incidences or those things kind of like playing in my mind.

19:44.396 --> 19:56.531
And like Liz said, I had to make a choice to forgive because those people were living their lives on their own, not even caring about me or whatever.

19:57.372 --> 19:58.674
Or I found out that.

19:59.074 --> 20:02.337
I wasn't able to pray as I needed to.

20:02.718 --> 20:05.200
And, you know, so many other things were happening.

20:06.021 --> 20:11.106
So, forgiveness actually takes the involvement of God.

20:12.587 --> 20:15.450
It causes, I believe, that it's actually spiritual.

20:15.830 --> 20:18.713
You need God's help to forgive sometimes.

20:19.314 --> 20:23.217
So, I asked God, how do I let go of this heart?

20:23.858 --> 20:26.200
And God told me, kind of like, I felt that.

20:26.761 --> 20:27.922
I should pray for them.

20:28.098 --> 20:32.865
Any time those thoughts played in my mind, I needed to pray for them.

20:33.426 --> 20:35.009
And that's what I started doing.

20:35.409 --> 20:39.235
So when the thoughts came in my mind, I would just pray for them.

20:40.036 --> 20:45.384
And slowly, the hearts, every time I pray for them, the heart will subside.

20:46.686 --> 20:52.054
So that's the way I've actually dealt with having to give forgiveness.

20:52.074 --> 20:53.016
It is a choice.

20:54.178 --> 20:57.042
And I'll tell us a story quickly.

20:57.186 --> 20:58.248
because of Time Boss.

20:58.268 --> 21:01.374
I don't know if you've ever heard of a person called Kori Temboom.

21:02.816 --> 21:05.381
Yeah, a lot of us have heard her story.

21:05.962 --> 21:12.114
She and her family, they were in, this happened during the Second World War.

21:12.775 --> 21:17.003
And they used to give refuge to Jews from the Nazi.

21:17.383 --> 21:21.010
And anyway, long story short,

21:21.634 --> 21:24.758
they were betrayed by some people.

21:24.778 --> 21:33.588
And then Nazis basically took them to the concentration camp and she lost her dad, she lost her sister in the concentration camp.

21:33.608 --> 21:39.454
And when she was released after the war, she went to a church and she was talking about forgiveness.

21:40.976 --> 21:49.586
And then on one occasion, one of the guards that actually been involved in, they would actually stand

21:50.146 --> 22:07.648
God, so this guy basically, and his colleagues, they would stand and watch the ladies having their shower, and they're basically what they want involved in dishumanizing Corey and the rest of her people.

22:07.668 --> 22:15.378
So they went through a lot of trauma, but then she saw this guy in church, and the guy

22:15.586 --> 22:24.156
After she had delivered her message about forgiveness, this guy actually came to her and straight out his hand and said, your message really taught me.

22:24.516 --> 22:26.058
And he had become a Christian.

22:26.078 --> 22:31.044
And she said her hand actually froze.

22:31.144 --> 22:37.932
She could not physically raise her hand to like take his hand because all those images kept playing on her mind.

22:38.773 --> 22:43.058
And she had to rely on God to help her forgive.

22:43.458 --> 22:48.605
And when she eventually did stretch out her hand, she said it was like a miracle took place.

22:49.847 --> 22:57.276
She felt this overwhelming, like something go over her and reach out to this guy.

22:57.297 --> 23:01.642
And she actually loved him, which I kind of like supernatural love.

23:02.383 --> 23:07.410
So like Liz said, forgiveness is a choice.

23:07.714 --> 23:18.171
But depending on the level of the heart, you can actually be hard to the extent that you actually need to rely on God to help you forgive.

23:18.872 --> 23:20.014
Yeah.

23:20.034 --> 23:21.016
That's an amazing answer.

23:21.076 --> 23:21.536
Thank you.

23:22.798 --> 23:23.139
Thank you.

23:28.027 --> 23:34.898
I think it's always important when we talk about the topic of forgiveness that

23:35.234 --> 23:38.118
Forgiveness is not the same thing as reconciliation.

23:38.979 --> 23:44.727
Those two things aren't the same, but they can be banded around as though they're one and the same thing, but they really aren't.

23:45.548 --> 23:52.978
And we always like to say this in Skylar Church, that we are a church that stands against domestic abuse in all of its forms.

23:54.059 --> 23:59.026
And we know that when you read a Bible verse like, how many times should I forgive

23:59.330 --> 24:04.855
My brother Peter says, you know, 70 times, no, 70 times, seven or whatever, you know, 490 times.

24:04.935 --> 24:06.577
How many times am I supposed to do this?

24:06.637 --> 24:07.838
And you can be banded around it.

24:07.878 --> 24:12.062
It's completely biblical to not only forgive, but to put yourself back in harm's way.

24:12.483 --> 24:13.544
We don't believe in that here.

24:14.344 --> 24:21.351
We believe that forgiveness is key, but forgiveness and reconciliation and restored relationship are not the same thing.

24:22.052 --> 24:28.498
And if you are struggling with that in any way and you'd love somebody to speak to Eddie and her team will be very happy.

24:28.706 --> 24:32.972
to journey with you, to listen to you, to pray with you, and to help you from that situation.

24:33.914 --> 24:35.636
Okay, so let's get on to that topic then.

24:35.917 --> 24:39.582
What is the difference between forgiveness and reconciliation?

24:44.369 --> 24:47.073
To the filter of whatever it is they did.

24:47.934 --> 24:58.610
Reconciliation is a restored relationship, and although we have been reconciled to God when He forgave us, it's not necessarily wisdom to be

24:59.138 --> 25:03.762
reconciled to somebody that's done something that's harmed you.

25:05.244 --> 25:09.808
So it's two completely separate things.

25:10.429 --> 25:20.358
It's the same as we talk about forgive and forget, but we cannot choose to forget, because the minute you think about forgetting something, you have remembered it.

25:20.939 --> 25:28.306
So we cannot,

25:28.514 --> 25:34.761
We cannot but forgive because that is what God has told us to do.

25:35.482 --> 25:47.496
But he has not told us to reconcile with people who have damaged us or hurt us or done something to us that has left us in a worse position.

25:47.536 --> 25:52.882
And we might talk about being, asking for forgiveness with a work colleague.

25:53.122 --> 25:55.104
And there was a reconciliation there.

25:55.244 --> 25:56.145
And that was great.

25:56.185 --> 25:59.209
I mean, if there is a reconciliation, it's a wonderful thing.

25:59.709 --> 26:02.793
But you have to be wise about where you reconcile, I think.

26:04.335 --> 26:05.236
Yeah, just that.

26:05.316 --> 26:06.117
It's a wisdom.

26:06.237 --> 26:09.621
And it's they are nothing to do with each other.

26:10.081 --> 26:12.043
You can't reconcile if you haven't forgiven.

26:12.083 --> 26:15.708
But forgiveness does not necessarily mean you then reconcile.

26:19.532 --> 26:19.912
Thank you.

26:20.313 --> 26:21.394
Thank you.

26:21.570 --> 26:24.493
A big example, I think, that really affected our lives.

26:25.574 --> 26:39.106
Half of many years ago, late 70s, William Wales, went to Wales out to set up a company, a good friend of mine, old friend of mine, since I was 11, and invited me to join him.

26:39.307 --> 26:40.328
He was a cabinet maker.

26:40.768 --> 26:43.370
We had a factory in Wales that employed about seven people.

26:45.873 --> 26:49.276
We sold a house in Enfield there.

26:49.797 --> 26:51.378
I bought plants and equipment.

26:51.618 --> 26:55.322
And I did everything else that Adrian didn't.

26:55.342 --> 26:59.847
He was brilliant designing furniture and this sort of thing.

27:00.728 --> 27:04.352
But he was sort of these days a bit manic depressive, you see.

27:04.492 --> 27:06.454
So I thought I could manage that.

27:07.235 --> 27:07.916
He's brilliant.

27:07.936 --> 27:08.997
He had his ups and downs.

27:09.678 --> 27:13.462
But got to a point where he just wanted me out of the company actually.

27:13.722 --> 27:16.185
It was a rift coming up to Christmas of all times.

27:17.166 --> 27:20.690
And I remember there was a row in the

27:20.994 --> 27:23.938
in the workshop, as it were, and is walking around with a hammer.

27:23.998 --> 27:26.842
You could really be, and his eyes glazed.

27:26.902 --> 27:27.784
I can see them now.

27:28.585 --> 27:29.446
So that was it, really.

27:29.486 --> 27:36.977
So I thought, with a company's situation like that, you have agreements, joints and several.

27:37.017 --> 27:39.721
And I could see us losing everything.

27:39.781 --> 27:42.945
So I left and got the job.

27:43.466 --> 27:44.948
Basically spent three or four months.

27:45.469 --> 27:49.074
The situation was, we had, back in,

27:49.634 --> 27:53.019
and Matthew, and that's of under five.

27:53.059 --> 27:56.865
The van was pregnant with Hannah, and she was born in February.

27:58.147 --> 28:02.313
And so that was that we went to our own way.

28:02.333 --> 28:05.699
And that's how we came to Chelmsen here.

28:06.219 --> 28:09.384
So we came here in August of that year.

28:09.424 --> 28:14.692
So we've become Christians then a couple of years later.

28:15.494 --> 28:18.418
So forgiveness, we were down in

28:18.562 --> 28:22.967
Nothing happened, actually, apart from the fact that the company went, broke two years later.

28:23.007 --> 28:27.933
Next thing I know, I've got the letter of my solicitor's, but that was that.

28:29.215 --> 28:30.557
I thought it was a good acclaim, you think?

28:30.597 --> 28:33.961
And he carried on, and basically he was better by himself.

28:34.021 --> 28:43.352
He had a small holding up on the west coast, and he was mending instruments, basically, all this stuff.

28:43.873 --> 28:45.134
Anyway, forgiveness.

28:45.595 --> 28:48.018
That was a bit of background to get to where we're going.

28:48.258 --> 28:55.948
And so we were at a Christian conference in those days called Royal Week, down in Wade Bridge.

28:56.488 --> 28:58.991
I mean, those places, the tensions to get blown away.

28:59.072 --> 29:00.173
Great, lovely time.

29:00.193 --> 29:00.974
It's all new for us.

29:01.815 --> 29:08.283
On the way back, we thought, well, we'll go up to Wales then, Utah, and just see them.

29:08.584 --> 29:09.324
I was curious.

29:10.206 --> 29:16.914
And the idea of forgiveness, reconciliation was in my mind, because we had no contact with them for 10 years.

29:17.058 --> 29:20.321
And I can't remember the detail, but it was amicable.

29:20.361 --> 29:29.490
And for me, that was the forgiveness aspect, as it were, but as to be reconciled, we never saw them again.

29:29.550 --> 29:37.458
There was no genie set of... At some point, we can still be friends, can't we?

29:38.459 --> 29:38.679
No.

29:38.719 --> 29:42.322
This had broken a friendship.

29:42.943 --> 29:46.066
Whilst I was reconciled to that fact,

29:46.146 --> 29:51.913
And I know that reconciliation is about two people, like a period of estrangement coming together in a way.

29:51.933 --> 29:59.744
I had in my mind forgiven him, and I'd been on Malice at all, but we lived 200 miles away.

29:59.764 --> 30:01.746
I had a new life now.

30:02.027 --> 30:03.368
The family had a new life.

30:03.749 --> 30:05.851
I wasn't going to continue that.

30:05.932 --> 30:14.002
So there is loss here, and I wasn't going to really establish that relationship.

30:14.114 --> 30:14.715
Thank you.

30:14.735 --> 30:19.942
And I don't know what happened to the rest of the family, much as I love them all, but there is...

30:20.523 --> 30:22.786
There is a difference between forgiveness and reconciliation.

30:22.946 --> 30:24.789
I'll keep it moving.

30:24.849 --> 30:26.191
I just want to...

30:27.793 --> 30:32.700
I've been thinking a lot recently, actually, about the forgiveness that we receive from God.

30:32.740 --> 30:34.883
When we repent, when we say to Him, I'm sorry.

30:35.924 --> 30:39.069
I turn from that way of living and I'm going to make a change.

30:39.089 --> 30:39.950
I'm going to change this.

30:40.551 --> 30:42.994
Our forgiveness from God is immediate.

30:43.874 --> 30:45.936
It's immediate, it's unbelievable, it's incredible.

30:46.997 --> 30:53.804
And that sometimes I think we can think therefore our sins against God don't have a consequence because we're forgiven.

30:54.344 --> 30:55.445
But actually that isn't true.

30:56.286 --> 31:06.376
Because if there are sins, if there are things we do wrong, this may be a bit complicated, but if there are things that we do wrong and they don't have a consequence, then that's injustice.

31:06.396 --> 31:07.658
And God is a just God.

31:08.498 --> 31:12.082
And so maybe the reason Moses couldn't go into the promised land is because

31:12.418 --> 31:16.543
God is a just God and they needed to be a consequence for His action.

31:16.563 --> 31:22.930
But for us living this side of the cross, it can be easy for us to think, well, therefore our sins, our shortcomings, whatever.

31:22.970 --> 31:25.453
They don't have a consequence, but they do.

31:25.754 --> 31:29.378
The difference is our consequence is laid on Jesus on the cross.

31:30.219 --> 31:36.306
And that's why Paul can write, look, because we've been forgiven, does it mean we should go on sinning and go on sinning and go on sinning?

31:36.426 --> 31:39.890
No, because there are still consequences for actions.

31:40.258 --> 31:44.823
And that is that our actions towards God, our sins are shortcomings.

31:44.843 --> 31:46.124
They go on to Jesus.

31:46.164 --> 31:48.767
They continue to be placed on Jesus at the cross.

31:49.388 --> 31:52.892
Sins always have a consequence, but thank God for Jesus.

31:53.452 --> 32:00.660
And sometimes you hear people say, well, look, I've said, sorry, if you're going to forgive me, why does the consequence go on?

32:00.700 --> 32:03.643
Because there is always a consequence of some degree.

32:03.663 --> 32:06.807
And that's what the process of reconciliation looks like.

32:07.628 --> 32:09.650
I read about,

32:10.210 --> 32:12.473
the fact that God can see our hearts.

32:13.534 --> 32:15.357
He knows if you're repentant immediately.

32:16.077 --> 32:18.721
If you repent, he can see your heart.

32:19.362 --> 32:21.785
He knows your repentance and he can offer that straight away.

32:22.185 --> 32:26.010
We aren't God and we can't see somebody's heart.

32:26.791 --> 32:28.453
And so for us, it takes time.

32:28.493 --> 32:38.706
The forgiveness takes place, but we have to go on a journey of time to see if there has been a heart change that we can trust and therefore we can be restored in relationship.

32:39.266 --> 32:40.147
It's different for us.

32:40.227 --> 32:40.908
We are not called.

32:40.928 --> 32:46.093
We can't do it straight away, but we're still called to do the best that we can and keep journeying this stuff through.

32:46.734 --> 32:49.577
Okay, let's have a look at another question from these legends.

32:52.240 --> 32:52.761
Let's go.

32:52.801 --> 32:57.126
Okay, what does it look like for us?

32:57.166 --> 32:58.547
I'm moving down all the way to eight, Liz.

32:58.867 --> 32:59.889
Not that you've got a list there.

33:00.469 --> 33:01.190
Ticking it off anyway.

33:02.451 --> 33:04.013
Bola, I'm going to you first.

33:04.714 --> 33:08.498
What does it look like in our lives when we choose not to forgive?

33:11.202 --> 33:25.198
The choice not to forgive, first of all, is I would almost like call it a scene because God actually asks us to forgive.

33:26.719 --> 33:36.530
Regardless of what the situation might be, there are so many scriptures in the Bible that actually God commands us to forgive.

33:37.391 --> 33:39.954
And we're actually looking at the laws

33:40.098 --> 33:50.189
the last prayer at the moment, and in there it tells us to forgive, because if we don't forgive, we more or less will not receive the forgiveness of God.

33:50.269 --> 33:55.155
So we are actually harming ourselves if we don't forgive.

33:55.455 --> 33:56.376
That's what it looks like.

33:56.977 --> 34:03.244
The consequences boomerang back to us are not necessarily the person that we are holding a grudge against.

34:03.304 --> 34:09.010
The other thing there is that when we don't forgive, we are almost like

34:09.154 --> 34:18.187
opening the door to the devil because we've shot out God from, I mean, we're in disobedience more or less.

34:19.209 --> 34:25.358
So what that then looks like, it's an open door for the devil to come in.

34:26.179 --> 34:34.792
It brings in strife, it brings in health problems and so many things as a consequence.

34:35.473 --> 34:38.738
I mean, if I was angry with somebody, I'll probably have

34:39.170 --> 34:44.779
Every time I see that person, I probably have high blood pressure or something, you know, because I'm stressed.

34:45.720 --> 34:55.295
And all of those things then have, you know, that health consequence, you know, I would be really upset every time I see that person, you know.

34:55.816 --> 34:58.600
So that's what it looks like on forgiveness.

34:59.081 --> 35:02.987
It's an open door for the devil to come in and have his way.

35:03.007 --> 35:03.969
Fantastic answer.

35:03.989 --> 35:04.329
Thank you.

35:04.429 --> 35:04.850
Liz.

35:08.738 --> 35:11.723
the health consequences can be more than just high blood pressure.

35:12.143 --> 35:25.924
There's been quite a bit of research done about different illnesses that can be rooted in unforgiveness because our body is in stress all the time when we're in a situation of unforgiveness.

35:26.024 --> 35:31.973
So as I said right at the beginning, when we forgive the person who gains most is us.

35:32.855 --> 35:34.597
Not the person that we forgive.

35:34.617 --> 35:36.620
They may never know that they've done anything to hurt us.

35:36.640 --> 35:37.682
They may never know that

35:37.762 --> 35:38.703
that we've forgiven them.

35:39.965 --> 35:43.750
But it's the result in here.

35:43.950 --> 35:47.815
And so unforgiveness is like having a burden.

35:47.976 --> 35:51.480
It's like having a walking around with a sack on your back.

35:52.442 --> 35:54.965
It's just a heaviness that comes.

35:55.065 --> 35:56.307
So, yeah.

35:56.427 --> 35:58.630
And it's not easy to forgive.

35:59.010 --> 36:07.762
Sometimes we say we're sorry and it's very trite because what we're saying we're sorry for

36:07.938 --> 36:09.662
is something that is fairly minimal.

36:09.822 --> 36:20.546
But when we are wanting somebody, when we are wanting to offer forgiveness to somebody, we don't have to tell them that I was having a conversation with a friend on Friday.

36:20.586 --> 36:22.450
And she said, she said, I was

36:22.530 --> 36:30.944
when she was part of this church, she said, and this lady bounced up to me and said, I've forgiven you and they've bounced away again.

36:30.964 --> 36:33.148
And she said, I've no idea what I did.

36:33.168 --> 36:36.493
I still to this, they don't know what I've done, what I've forgiven them all.

36:36.874 --> 36:45.929
So you don't always have to explain what it is and you don't always have to speak to the person who you are forgiven because it's something that you know internally that you need to do.

36:46.510 --> 36:48.914
I can remember an incident years ago now where

36:49.314 --> 36:52.878
I was having coffee with somebody, and they said something to me.

36:53.039 --> 36:55.602
I can still picture exactly where I was.

36:55.982 --> 36:58.786
They said something to me, and it was like I'd been stabbed in the back.

36:58.906 --> 37:00.348
It was so painful.

37:01.509 --> 37:09.239
And then the conversation sort of carried on, and I went away, and I spoke to Bev about it, and I said, I don't know what to do about this, because it's a person I need to be in relationship with.

37:09.979 --> 37:12.462
But that was so, so painful.

37:12.883 --> 37:18.610
And she said, you have to forgive them, and I looked at it, and I thought, yeah, yeah, okay.

37:18.690 --> 37:19.892
be quite as direct as that.

37:20.192 --> 37:23.516
So I had to work at it.

37:23.556 --> 37:26.680
I had to work at choosing to forgive this person.

37:27.041 --> 37:32.247
I have never told them what they did and I have never told them I've forgiven them because they had no idea that they had hurt me.

37:33.048 --> 37:38.695
And God was really gracious because I actually cannot remember what it was that was done.

37:38.735 --> 37:40.918
I think sometimes God does allow you to forget.

37:40.978 --> 37:47.026
You can't choose to forget because sometimes God gives you that blessing and you cannot remember.

37:47.138 --> 37:49.481
And that's what happened in that incident.

37:49.521 --> 37:51.744
But it was hard to do.

37:53.105 --> 37:53.686
Thank you, Liz.

37:54.067 --> 37:58.232
Oh, Liz, by the way, I know somebody just as direct who would tell me what I needed to do.

37:58.592 --> 37:59.633
Can't think of who that might be.

38:00.034 --> 38:04.059
Anyway, if you could pass that on to Mike.

38:05.180 --> 38:05.381
Always.

38:05.841 --> 38:06.182
No need.

38:07.523 --> 38:07.824
Yes.

38:08.825 --> 38:13.651
Just to say, I agree, absolutely what Bola and Liz have just said.

38:14.272 --> 38:16.274
But coming here this morning,

38:16.482 --> 38:29.163
This notion, if you like righteous equilibrium, if you're not forgiving people, you sort of get a bit out of kilter with God as it were.

38:29.183 --> 38:37.697
I go back to the, you know, that commandment to love the Lord God with all your heart, mind and soul and love your name as yourself.

38:38.578 --> 38:43.506
And it's as though if there's something to have done, is it where you've,

38:43.810 --> 38:54.343
a clumsy explanation, but you're sort of slightly out of kilter with God because we ask to be righteous before him and live a life of righteousness.

38:55.324 --> 38:57.447
You know, his will, not mine.

38:58.068 --> 39:00.211
And so that is a process.

39:01.132 --> 39:12.626
And so it's sensing that really and seeking him, as Bola was saying, that only God can help you actually forgive sometimes, perhaps all the time.

39:13.474 --> 39:15.476
It's great.

39:15.496 --> 39:16.597
Thank you.

39:16.617 --> 39:16.878
Thank you.

39:16.898 --> 39:18.760
I'm going to throw a question in that's not on my list.

39:19.340 --> 39:20.261
Everyone's favorite thing.

39:20.321 --> 39:22.283
So you can grab the mic if you want it.

39:24.185 --> 39:37.699
When we forgive each other and we journey with each other, if that's the right outcome towards reconciliation, what process, what job does time have in the whole process?

39:37.719 --> 39:40.402
What do you think about time?

39:41.154 --> 39:43.718
instantaneous versus how long things should take.

39:43.778 --> 39:51.308
Have you got anything to add to people who are just trying to journey that through and just wondering about the process and where the time has a part to play?

39:56.736 --> 40:06.690
So I think the further you get away from the incident, sometimes it lessens the pain of it and therefore is easier to forgive.

40:08.092 --> 40:09.874
But also, of course, if you're

40:10.242 --> 40:17.393
if you've got a distance in time, then the chances are you've got a distance in the relationship, the relationship has severed.

40:18.094 --> 40:24.884
So there's that thing about don't go to sleep on your anger, you know, use at wedding services sometimes.

40:25.425 --> 40:39.346
So because the person you're marrying is the person that you are having to live with and be in the same thing, you cannot afford for there to be a time lag between

40:40.130 --> 40:45.597
the incident and the forgiveness because it just sours the relationship.

40:46.678 --> 41:06.002
So I think it's a question of the closer the person is, the more in your life they are, the more important it is that the forgiveness happens quickly and it clears the deck.

41:06.370 --> 41:15.101
But that, on the other hand, you've still got this whole problem of when something happens, you've got layers as to how it's impacted you.

41:15.141 --> 41:18.405
But talking's a great thing, isn't it?

41:18.425 --> 41:23.772
To be able to talk to somebody and say, when you did that, it really hurt me.

41:23.792 --> 41:26.515
And I'm not really sure quite what the impact is.

41:26.575 --> 41:29.078
But as far as I can, I choose to forgive you.

41:29.118 --> 41:35.506
And I may need to come back and forgive you for something more when I've processed it.

41:36.130 --> 41:37.953
Thank you, Liz, for taking that one off the cuff.

41:38.394 --> 41:44.485
I'd love for us to look at how to apologise well, because I think that's really a key thing.

41:45.187 --> 41:50.456
Of course, we can look at remorse versus repentance.

41:50.476 --> 41:53.682
Sometimes we can be remorseful over our actions.

41:53.858 --> 41:55.320
as opposed to repentance.

41:55.460 --> 41:57.183
And repentant is like a heart change.

41:57.223 --> 41:59.446
Remorseful feels, I wish I hadn't been caught.

41:59.907 --> 42:06.476
So I'm remorseful that it took place because of this situation, as opposed to because I'm having my heart challenged.

42:06.496 --> 42:09.480
So we can look at remorse and repentance in a little bit if we still have time.

42:09.560 --> 42:12.084
But that gave you time to think about apologies.

42:12.524 --> 42:15.248
How do we apologize well?

42:15.488 --> 42:16.250
How should we do that?

42:18.112 --> 42:19.394
Well, how's it got the mind cast up?

42:19.975 --> 42:22.258
So it's...

42:23.074 --> 42:30.225
it's taking responsibility for what we have done or said and not finding an excuse in that.

42:30.646 --> 42:40.661
So I'm sorry I did that, but if you haven't done that, I wouldn't have, you know, it's actually, I am sorry for doing that, full stop.

42:41.923 --> 42:49.234
I am not putting any blame on you for the fact that I have responded this way because that

42:49.538 --> 42:54.283
then makes them the guilty party for instigating the fact that you now feel like this.

42:55.525 --> 42:59.209
And the fact that I feel like this is because it's me.

42:59.729 --> 43:05.155
So the same thing may have happened between you and somebody else and they didn't feel hurt by it.

43:05.235 --> 43:07.278
But when it was you and me, it hurt.

43:07.658 --> 43:10.982
And so it's money issue, not your issue.

43:11.522 --> 43:16.768
So I think it's being plain.

43:16.828 --> 43:18.290
I am sorry.

43:19.330 --> 43:20.612
I shouldn't have said that.

43:20.712 --> 43:21.634
I shouldn't have done that.

43:22.495 --> 43:29.086
I choose to ask you to forgive me, but I'm not putting any blame on you for the fact that that's how I responded.

43:29.827 --> 43:30.969
Great, great answer.

43:31.029 --> 43:32.912
Thank you, Liz.

43:32.932 --> 43:33.833
Thank you.

43:33.854 --> 43:37.399
Yes, let me ask to be, I think, forgiven.

43:37.840 --> 43:44.050
It's because you, the other aspect of this is you love that person and you still want to

43:44.930 --> 43:51.117
look good in their sight, as it were, to be, and if you've upset them in some way, you've damaged the relationship.

43:51.217 --> 44:02.671
So, as you say, it's about opening up to what you've done wrong and saying, an unconditional forgiveness, you know, please forgive me for doing that, you know.

44:02.691 --> 44:12.562
And I think it comes out of love for the other person, because you could have another example where

44:13.474 --> 44:14.916
It's somebody you met in the street.

44:15.818 --> 44:17.821
But even then, you should...

44:18.702 --> 44:19.604
They're still a neighbour.

44:20.725 --> 44:23.710
I'm thinking this real as I'm talking, and you should still...

44:23.730 --> 44:25.733
I'm sorry, I bumped into you.

44:26.594 --> 44:27.997
Sorry, I knocked you off your bike.

44:31.262 --> 44:31.782
That's brilliant.

44:32.303 --> 44:38.833
Thank you very much.

44:38.853 --> 44:41.778
I've been married for almost 22 years now, so I'm well versed in

44:42.082 --> 44:43.484
making apologies, then.

44:43.644 --> 44:48.231
Yeah, I know a lot of that.

44:48.251 --> 44:53.699
But it helps, though, if you're married to one of the best people in the, I mean, I'm married to the best woman in the world.

44:54.661 --> 44:55.863
She told me to say that.

44:58.206 --> 44:59.969
I'm just joking, I'm just joking.

45:01.551 --> 45:03.334
Just joking.

45:03.354 --> 45:04.916
I hope I'm not gonna be doggos.

45:08.121 --> 45:08.882
Okay, well,

45:09.506 --> 45:35.122
making apologies, it means a 180 degree turnaround, you know, because if you're used to apologizing about something and then you go back to do it again, eventually even the person you're apologizing to, we know that this guy does, or this person really doesn't mean it, so

45:35.970 --> 45:42.920
Apologizing actually means doing a turnaround and making a decision not to do it again.

45:42.940 --> 46:00.024
And like Lee said, also making an apology means not pointing fingers to say, sorry, I did this, but I did this because you did that.

46:00.664 --> 46:00.945
No.

46:02.387 --> 46:04.690
Like she said, own it and

46:05.346 --> 46:07.349
End of story, you know.

46:07.369 --> 46:09.753
So that's fantastic.

46:09.833 --> 46:10.293
Thank you.

46:10.394 --> 46:10.694
Thank you.

46:10.714 --> 46:15.201
I've got one more question for these guys before we come into a time of communion together.

46:16.102 --> 46:17.765
And this is a really broad one.

46:17.805 --> 46:19.267
It was the last one that I sent through to you.

46:19.307 --> 46:23.554
What are some of the greatest lessons that you've learned about forgiveness over the years?

46:31.265 --> 46:34.450
Keep sure it counts.

46:34.626 --> 46:36.508
They don't let the sun go down on your anger.

46:37.369 --> 46:46.920
Yeah, keeping short accounts, just living in a, I suppose it's a sort of state of grace.

46:47.541 --> 46:52.306
So, again, this person was having coffee with this today on Friday.

46:52.386 --> 47:02.738
She said, I think the Catholics have got something when it comes to confession, you know, that whole getting stuff off your chest thing and actually owning

47:03.266 --> 47:04.828
Only new and responsibility.

47:05.829 --> 47:09.894
There's something in that when I sit and have coffee.

47:09.914 --> 47:13.798
I no longer, the poor not being around, I no longer have him as a sounding board.

47:14.279 --> 47:19.024
So, you know, having good friends that I can actually say, I'm really struggling with this.

47:19.384 --> 47:20.185
This has hurt me.

47:20.245 --> 47:21.347
What am I going to do about it?

47:21.827 --> 47:31.378
I think just having that sort of place where you can be safe and be open and honest about how you feel is a vital importance.

47:31.586 --> 47:33.548
having somebody that you can lean into.

47:34.329 --> 47:39.553
We've all got God, but we may not all have God, and we all have God available to us.

47:40.955 --> 47:49.483
But it's not quite the same as having somebody put their arm around you and comfort you and help you to work process when you've been hurt or when you need to forgive.

47:50.524 --> 47:51.264
That's great, thanks.

47:51.345 --> 47:55.228
In James, it says that we should confess our sins to each other.

47:55.268 --> 48:01.394
And having a culture where you can actually be open and honest with each other and talk through stuff is a massive part.

48:01.794 --> 48:04.758
of being able to take ownership of the things that we need forgiveness for.

48:05.639 --> 48:08.602
Freddie, any sort of big final hits from you?

48:09.744 --> 48:16.452
I was talking to Val about this, actually, about, you know, why should I forgive them when they didn't know what they did wrong, as it were?

48:16.472 --> 48:21.779
And Val talked about, well, it will affect your attitude towards them.

48:22.760 --> 48:27.746
And so, as Liz says, it's always good to keep short accounts.

48:28.607 --> 48:30.930
And that's all to say, really.

48:31.170 --> 48:31.610
Fantastic.

48:31.630 --> 48:32.852
I don't follow any final thoughts from you.

48:33.452 --> 48:34.434
No, we are all done.

48:34.454 --> 48:36.736
Shall we give our amazing panel a round of applause?

48:36.956 --> 48:37.577
Thank you guys.

48:56.397 --> 48:57.298
It's a big topic.

48:57.442 --> 48:57.862
It's huge.

48:58.203 --> 48:59.804
So many things we didn't get to discuss.

49:00.285 --> 49:05.670
But there were so many things for us to discuss in our life group settings with our friends over a cup of coffee.

49:05.730 --> 49:07.952
Let's just talk and work out what this stuff looks like.

49:10.354 --> 49:14.578
Forgive us our sins as we forgive those who sin against us.

49:15.539 --> 49:17.801
We're going to come into a time of communion now.

49:18.382 --> 49:21.905
So I think the youth are going to be fetched, some of the older youth.

49:25.168 --> 49:26.930
In just a moment, we can have an opportunity

49:27.010 --> 49:32.098
on this Remembrance Sunday to pause and remember and reflect on Jesus.

49:32.679 --> 49:36.686
Three stations set up, gluten-free bread is everywhere.

49:36.786 --> 49:53.394
And at the right time, I'd love to invite us to leave our seats and to go, ones, twos, family groups, friendship groups, whoever you'd like to, to have communion together, to pause, to remember the sacrifice that Jesus paid for us so that we could have life.

49:55.682 --> 49:57.865
In 1 Corinthians 11 it says this.

50:02.330 --> 50:05.293
For I received from the Lord what I also passed on to you.

50:06.295 --> 50:14.364
The Lord Jesus on the night he was betrayed took bread and when he had given thanks he broke it and said this is my body which is for you.

50:14.384 --> 50:16.487
Do this in remembrance of me.

50:16.527 --> 50:22.514
In the same way after supper he took the cup saying this cup is the new covenant in my blood.

50:23.138 --> 50:33.169
Do this whenever you drink it in remembrance of me, for whenever you eat this bread and drink this cup, you proclaim the Lord's death until he comes."

50:35.672 --> 50:42.579
Now, when Jesus actually broke the bread in that last supper, he also mentioned forgiveness.

50:42.599 --> 50:46.663
It says this in Matthew 26, while they were eating, Jesus took bread.

50:47.224 --> 50:52.690
And when he had given thanks, he broke it and gave it to his disciples saying, take and eat,

50:52.834 --> 50:53.815
This is my body.

50:54.656 --> 51:00.101
Then he took the cup and when he had given thanks, he gave it to them saying, drink from it all of you.

51:00.501 --> 51:06.487
This is my blood of the covenant, which is poured out for many for the forgiveness of sins.

51:07.408 --> 51:21.522
So on this day when we're remembering how to forgive and how to apologize and what this journey looks like for us, let us remember above all that we are forgiven because of the broken body and the blood poured out of Jesus.

51:21.794 --> 51:24.661
that has brought us life in all its fullness.

51:26.185 --> 51:35.730
So why don't we, I'd like to invite the band back up.

